{"/service/ndnp/deu/batch_deu_groot_ver01/data/sn87062224/0051415689A/1958050901/0574.xml":{"full_text":"Men Junior Counselors\nSelected At University\ni.\n(continued from page one)\nIn 1951 the junior counselor pro\ngram was initiated at Delaware\namong the women students. The\nmen's counseling program began\nIn 1956 and has made rapid pro\ngress since that date. Junior coun\nselors begin their work even be\nfore freshmen orientation week,\ncorresponding with their advisees\nduring the summer months prior\nto their_ arrival. Their assistance\ncontinues throughout the year and\nis an important adjunct to the\nwork of tne professional counsel\nors in the dean of students office\nand the faculty advisers of the\nnewly enrolled students.\nA preparatory course for the new\ncounselors will be held in three\nsessions d\u00fcrftig the spring under\nthe direction of Miss Black. Dr.\nEdward OU, Dr. Jambs A. Flaherty,\nDr. Oordoi. Keppel and Mrs. Ger\naldine M. Wyatt.\nNew Counselors are: Lawrence\nJilk, son of Mr. and Mrs. L. T. Jilk,\n1211 Hilltop Avenue; John Son\ntowski, son of Mr. and Mrs. Fran\ncis Sontowskl, 1101 Coyne Place;\nDonald LaFashia, son of Mr. and\nMrs. Carl LaFashia, 1801 Beech\nStreet; William Hunt, son of Mr.\nand Mrs. John W. Abbott, 10-C\nCourt Drive, Lancaster Courts;\nJohn Russell, 4510 Roslyn Rd\u201e\nRolling Hills; Jay Wilde, son of\nMr. and Mrs. Samuel Wilde, 808 W.\n28th Street; Dennis Fuhr, son of\nMr. and Mrs. William, Fuhr, 117\nW. 19th St.; Robert Walsh, son of\nMr. and Mrs. Michael Walsh, 2700\nTatnall Street: Robert Stewart,\nson of Mr. and Mrs. Claude Stew\nart, 217 S. Bancroft Pkwy.; Wayne\nTatman, son of Mr. and Mrs. Dan\niel Tatman, Lands End Road, Sed\ngely Farms; Robert Griggs, son of\nMr. and Mrs. Albert B. Griggs, 411\nIrving Drive; Daniel Harwitz, son\nof Dr. and Mrs. Morris Harwitz,\n1314 N. Broom St.; Robert John\nson, son of Mr. and Mrs. J. W.\nJohnson, 3011 N. Van Buren\n'Street; James McGuinness, son of\nMr. and Mrs. James A. McGuin\nneas, 429 G.eddes St.; Gilbert Smith,\nson of Mr. and Mrs. Gilbert Smith,\nSr., 28 Boulder Brook Drive; Rich\nard Koch, son of Mr. aud Mfs. W.\nW. Koch, 6 Elm Avenue; Joseph\nSllwkowski, son of Mr. and Mrs.\nAnthony Sliwkowski, 1619 Chest\nnut St.\u2014all of Wilmington, Del\naware.\nMark Hurrn, son of Mr. and Mrs.\nD. C. Hurm, 115 Briar Lane; Wil\nliam Holland, son of Mr. and Mrs.\nWilliam R. Holland, 125 Brook\nside Boulevard\u2014both of Newark,\nDelaware.\nWilliam Brereton, son of Mr. and\nMrs. F. E. Brereton, 210 S. Front\nStreet, Milford, Del.; Lawrence\nCordrey, son of Mr. and Mrs. Ed\nward Cordrey, Millsboro, Del.;\nDavid Green, son of Mr. and Mrs.\nDavid Green, 977 S. State Street,\nDover, Del.; John Simian, son of\nMr. aud Mrs. Norman Sirman, R.\nD. No. 1, Delmar, Delaware; Don\nald Reed, con of Mr. and Mrs. Eu\ngene Reed, Cowglll's St., Dover,\nDel.; Howard Moyer, son of Mr.\nand Mrs. J. Milton Moyer, Dags\nboro, Del.; Stephen Welch, son of\nMr. and Mrs C, M. Welch, Jr., Mil\nford, Del,; Larry Erdner, son of\nMrs. Helen O. Krdner, 107 Helms\nStreet, Swedesboro, N. J. Edward\nSchmauder, son of Mr. and Mrs.\nEdward Schmauder, 416 Euclid\nt\nAvenue, Haddonfleld, N. J.; George\nCarlisle, son of Mr. and Mrs. E. J.\nCarlisle, 307 Pearl Street, Bridge\nton, N. J. John Mordas, son of Mr.\nand Mrs. Kostik Mordas, 27 East\nSt., South River, N. J. John Den\nyes, son of Mr. and Mrs. Russell\nDenyes, 35 Collinwood Rd.. Maple\nwood. N: ,J.; Richard Ashby, son\n'of Mr. and Mrs. E. S. Ashby, 26\nCampbell Rd., Short Hills, N. J.;\n\u2022Lloyd Bushay, son of Mr. and Mrs.\nIra C. Bushay, 505 S. Seaville\nRoad, Ocean View, N. J.; Scott\nWoodall, son of Mr. ,and Mrs. Si\nmon R. Woodall, Galena, Maryland;\nCharles Woodward, son of Mr. and\nMrs. Charles Woodward, 5010 Cop\nley Rd., .Philadelphia, Pa.; Fred\nerick Mainwaring, son of Mr.-and\nMrs. F. Mainwaring, 134 Scenic Rd.,\nSpringfield, Pa.; Thomas Gutshall,\nson of Mr. and Mrs. Joseph Gut\nshall, R. D. No. 2, Huntington,\nPa.; John BoVman, son of Mr. and\nMrs. John K. Bowman, 9 N. Pearl\nSt., York, Pa.; James Pork, son\nof Mr. and Mrs. John M. Park.\n1104 Concord Ave., Chester, Pa.;\nHarry Rivkin, son of Mr. and Mrs.\nWilliam Rivkin, 6715 N. 7th St..\nPhiladelphia, Pa., and David Keif\nfer, son of Mr. and Mrs. Eugene\nKelffer, 1314 N. 14th St., Reading,\nPi\n\n\u25a0vr.\nX\nvC\n\n8\nv\nGREETINGS\n\u2022re brought to you from\nFriendly Neighbors\n8 Civic Social Welfare\nLeaders\nthrough\nWELCOME WAGOTi\nGIFTS\n.a\ntv\nOn the occasion oft\nThe Birth of a Baby\nChange of residence\nArrivals of Newcomers te\nCity\nCorinne Fooks\nMilford\nPhone 4723\n\nLaura C. Waples t\nPhone 5714\nMilford\n(No cotI or obligation)\nNever a Dull\nMoment for\nTeen Crowd\ninvites autographs. The shirt may\nbe worn tucked in or straight-hang\ning, comes packaged witn a ball\npoint pen, handy for scrawling\nphone numbers and pictures.\nTeen Aiders: Youngsters of Sta\n.des High School, Westport, Conn.,\nhaw figured out a gimmick for\nfund-raising for the benefit of the\nAmerican Field Service Interna\nThe\nAP \u00bbwsfeatnres\nLet's take a rocket ride and see\nwhat's perking on teen fronts.\nFashion Fad: One kind of shirt\ntional Scholarship program,\nplan will make it possible for a\nStaples student to study abroad\nand a foreign student to live in\nWestport. Here's how it works:\nThe students have distributed\ncards to residents of the area offer\ning to work at jobs, including car\nwashing, removing storm windows,\nwashing dogs, ironing, baby sit\nting. outdoor work, providing $1\nfor every hour of their time is con\ntributed to the AFSISP.\nDieters Delight: Newest gim\nmick for student dieter\u00bb is to ask\nthe boy home for an afternoon\nsnack, instead of Joining him for\ntreats where one must admit one\nis on a diet. Make any flavored\ndrink ypu like with non-fat dry\nmilk, they say. All you do is pour\nthe milk crystals in a glass with\nice water, add low calorled lemon\nsherbet or other flavoring, a tea\nspoon of lemon juice and you have\na low-caloried between-meal snack.\nAdd some cherry juice if you'd like\na pink flavor.\nGirl Baseball: Junior baseball is\nnot limited to males. Girls up to 15\nyears old are playing lassieball, a\nform of softball. Tht pattern for\nthe Lassie Leaguers was begun in\n1963 by a retired industrialist. Last\nyear there were leagues in action\nIn Pennsylvania, California, Vir\nginia and Florida, and the idea is\nstill growing, expected to catch on\nin New England.\nPoster Passion: A new form of\nart with young people who can't\nafford Rembrandt or Corot or other\nold masters, is poster art. Bull\nfight posters painted by Ruano\nLlopif depicting famous positions\nand passes of memorable matadors\nare going on teen age walls. Some\nyoung people collect posters\u2014the\natre, bullfight, circus, etc.\nTeen Talk: You may add to your\nvocabulary these little tid-bits\nfrom a freshman at Skidmore Col\nlege\nIf a boy is dressed to a T, he's\nconsidered \"real shoe.\"\nIf he is overdressed, he is \"real\ngalosh\" (overshoe).\nIf he is underdressed, he is a\n\"poor sold.\"\nm\nCHEAPSKATE\nMARION, Ind. (JP Burl Peg\nden failed in attempts to get a pair\nof cigars from his brother Claude,\nafter receiving announcement say\ning Claude had become the father\nof twin boys. The announcement\nhad been mailed in 1946. I\npe/tfect uioi( tb pamper mother...\n\u00e7retU/bttUich coats\nand dusters J\n\nmm\n\ny\n\n\nA\nr\n\n\n4\n\nt\nRefreshing ways for Mother to begin\nevery day wearing one of our feminine,\nfashion-wise dusters or brunch coats.\nSelect now she'll be delighted.\nCotton print duster with belt to wear many\nways. Fitted brunch coat, in a beautiful rose\nprinted cotton. Mandarin chemise duster,\noriental-effect print, Brunch coat with\na Twenties-look, Easy-going duster of\ndotted cotton, with solid color trim.\n\n\u00dc\nm m\n\n\nf*\n\n\nI\n\nm\n\n1\n\nn\nm I\n8\n\n5#\nV.\n\n\nl\nV\n\u00ce\n:5\nI\nm m\n\nm \u00dc\n\nII\nm\nv!\nu\no\n\u25a0m\nr*\nj\n\ni\nm\n\nf\n(r.\nf\n14\nit s\nm\n-M i\nm\n\na\nm\nh\n111\n1!\ni\nu\nvi\nIS*\ni\nm\nf\n\n;V\n\n\n\n,1\nA i\nk\n\n'A.\nEmanuel's\n\nIK\nMILFORD\nDOVER\nt\noverbrook\nMrs. Howard Millman\nPhone Lewes 3898\nj Services at White's Chapel for\nI Sunday, May 11:\n1 Sunday School begins at 9:45 a.\nm. Superintendent, Howard West.\nMorning worship service begins\nat 10:45 o'clock. Pastor. Rev. Ken\nneth Dickey.\nThe WSCS of White's Chapel\nwill meet May 14. Wednesday eve\nin the basement of the church\npromptly at 8 p. m. All members\ncon e and make a special effort to\ninvite a guest. Others that are not\nmembers are invited to come and\nl\u00b0in in fellowship with the other\nIndies of the WSCS hoping tb see\na S\u00b0\u00b0d attendance.\nMr and Mrs. Roy Ellingsworth\naud Mr. an d Mrs. Willard Ellings\nwor th and son William were Mon\nday evening guests of Mr. and Mrs.\nHoward Millman and family.\nMr. and Mrs* Norman Neff were\nSaturday evening callers of Mr.\nand Mrs. Arthur Campbell.\nMr. and Mrs. Howard E. Mill\nman, Sr., and daughter Olive and\nMr. and Mrs. Minos T. Conoway\nattended the revival meetings at\nthe Church of God in Lewes on\nSaturday evening.\nMr. and Mrs. Harley Mitchell\nand Mrs. Thomas Mitchell visited\nher brother, Mr. and Mrs. John\nMitchell of Greenwood on Sunday.\nSunday callers of Mr, and Mrs.\nMarshall Willey and family were\nMr. and Mrs. Andrew Carpenter,\nMrs. Emma Carpenter and Miss\nHelen Willey, all of Milton, Mrs.\nRaymond Dayton and Mr. und Mrs.\nR\u00b0y Ellingsworth of Lewes\nThose on the sick list this week\nare Andy, Donna and Betty Willey,\nT\u00b0y ce Davidson and Melody Cono\nway, who all have the measles.\nMrs. Sara Pepper is also on the\nsick list.\nMr. and Mrs. George Chappell\nentertained to supper recently:\nMr. and Mrs. David Hastings a.;d\nsons, David and Keith -of George\ntown and Harry Hastings.\nMrs. Dorothy Hitch was the din\nner guest Wednesday of Mr. and\nMrs. Arthur Campbell.\nMr. and Mrs. Vincent White and\nfamily were dinner guests of Mr.\nand Mrs. Norman Neff on Sunday.\nMrs. Thomas Mitchell gave a\nturkey dinnex in honor of her hus\nband's 71st birthday on Saturday\nevening. Those attending were Mr.\nand Mrs. Leighton Lockerman,\nMr. and Mrs. Leslie Lockerman and\ntwo children, Ralph Steele and Mrs.\nCathrine Baker of Wilmington.\nMr. and Mrs. Albert Davidson\ncalled on Mr. and Mrs. Uhland Da\nvid son and Mr. and Mrs. Themas\nMitchell on Sunday.\nCarl Davidson spent Thursday\nevening with Mr. and Mrs. Artluir\nCampbell.\nMr. and Mrs. Arthur Hall of\nWilmington visited Mrs. Willard\nWhite Sunday.\nDR. FRANK L GOBLE\nChiropractic Physician\nDally 9 to 2\u2014Except Saturday\nEvenings: Monday, Wednesday and\nFriday: 7:30 to 9\nPHONE DOVER\n104 S. Bradford St., Dover\n2284\nDelaware\nMrs. Minnie Davidson and Mrs.\nEstella Johansen visited Mrs.\nMarguerite Moore of near St.\n.Johns on Friday.\nMiss Joan White accompanied\nBruce Trethewey of Rehoboth to\nWilmington on Sunday.\nMiss Betty Chappell spent Mon\nday evening with her parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. George C' appell.\nMr. and Mrs. Roland Millman\nspent Wednesday in Wilmington.\nMr. and Mrs. Minos Conoway\nvisited their daughter, Mrs. Mar\nguerite Moore on Thursday.\nDouglas Parsons of Syracuse, N T\nY., spent the week-end in Over\nbrook. He had dinner with Mrs.\nMinnie Davidson a^d Mrs. Estella\nJohansen on Saturday.\nMr. and Mrs. James Richards oi\nBaltimore visited George Chappell\nover the week-end.\nMrs. Warrington Vincent and\ndaughter Sara visited Mrs. Carlton\nWells and her new baby in the\nMilford Memorial HospUal on\nThursday.\nMr. and Mrs. Richard Hudson of j\nGeorgetown visited Mr. and Mrs.\nJoe Hudson and family on Mon-ivel;\nMr. and Mrs. Edward Millman\nday.\nand daughter, Terri Lyn were din\nner guests Sunday of Mr. and Mrs.\nRandy Talley of Lewes.\nWillard White, the chief engi\nneer on the pilot boat, is home for\ntwo weeks.\nMr. and Mrs. Howard Millman\nand Mrs. James West visited their\nmother, Mrs. Rufus Rust of Red\nden,. near Georgetown on Sunday.\nDavis Chorman and Nelsoi\nChorman were callers of Mr. and\nMrs. Arthu\" Campbell on Friday\nevening.\nMr. and Mrs. James Collins\ncalled on Mr. and Mrs*. Thomas Mit\nchell,Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. Philip Elliott of\nMagnolia, and son visited Mr. and\nMrs. Howard Millman on Wednes\nday.\nMr. and Mrs. Arthur Hall arriv\ned home Monday. They have been\nspending the winter months in\nGrant, Florida.\nMr. and Mrs. Howard E. Mill\nman, Jr., visited Mr. and Mrs. Phil\nip Elliott and son at Magnolia on\nSunday afternoon.\nForty-two per cent of the work\ning popqlation of Italy are farm\ners.\nHAVE YOU DISCOVERED THE GOOD EATING\nat the\nCOUNTRY KITCHEN\non Route 113 at Ellendaie Cross Roads\nWe Have a Good Variety\nincluding Beef, Lamb, Fresh Fish, Chicken\nQUANTITY BAKING FOR SPECIAL OCCASIONS\nI\nPies Cake\u00e0 Roils\nPHONE GREENWOOD 4837\n4-25-tf\nHOUSTON\nMrs. Viola Thistlewood\niPhone: Milford 4944\nA thought\u2014\"What is past is past.\nThere is a future left to all men,\nwho have the virtue to repenf and\nenergy to atone.\"\nChurch news for Mother's Day,\nSunday, May 11, Sabbath School at\n10:(0 a. m., Robert H. Yerkes, Sr.,\nGeneral Supt.; Alvin Brow\u00bb, Junior\nSupt.; Mrs. Charles Pearson, Cradle\nRo'll Supt.\nThe service of worship begin\nat 11 a. m., with the organ prelude,\nMrs. Agnes Webb at the organ. The\ncall to worship by the pastor. Rev.\nRay Kirwan. Special numbers will\nbe given by the Senior and Chancel\nchoirs and the minister will deliver\nthe sermon.\nThe minister and church commit\ntee gratefully acknowledge the fol\nlowing gifts for the church at the\ntime of its reopening: Piano, Chan\ncel and Junior Choirs; Collection\nPlates, Mr. and Mrs. x Clinton Mar\nThe American Flag Set, The\nAmerican Legion Auxiliary of Mil\nford; Two matching Hymn Boards,\nThe Methodist Youth Fellowship;\nNew Table Cross (illuminated), Mr.\nand Mrs. C. Walter Wharton; Cross\nfor the steeple, Mr. John Wage\nmaker; Bible Marker, Mr. and Mrs.\nJohn Roe; Pulpit Bible, Mrs. J.\nBenton Counselman. Any person\nor organization wishing to make a\nspecial gift is asked to contact the\nminister. Rev. Kirwan or the Board\nof Trustees.\nProgress is being made on the\nrestoration of the church and Sun\nday School building and we antici\npate being back in the sanctuary\nby sometime in June.\nThe work on the new addition to\nthe Sunday School Building has\nbeen started and the contract calls\nfor its completion by the end of\nSeptember.\nThe Methodist Men are sponsor\ning the two baseball teams again\nthis season. The team for boys up\nto twelve years of age will he\nmanaged by Charles Hayes with\nthe assistance of several oilier men.\nThe team for boys over twelve\nyears of age will be managed by\nReese Thistlewood. He will also\nhave some assistance. A meeting of\nthe boys of both groups will be\nheld very soon and the support of\nthe community in thi s project will\nbe greatly anpiceiat id.\n*unch at\nthe Simpson sal\u00ab- on Saturday, May\n10, beginning at 11 a. m. At the\nsame time, they will have a bake\nthere. Anyone wishing to contribute,\nto this bake, please contact some\nmember of the WSCS. Any assis\ntance will be greatly appreciated,\nMrs. Ruth Sapp substituted teach\ning the first and second grades for\nM rs. Massaferi. on Monday,\nio\"/\" n R d M?B PP Joh\" Fo?\"st a n t:i\ntendecT a meftfng of the Capt Jona\nthan Caid^eU Chapter DAR inthe\nMil?ord Century Club bu\u00fcdiig on\nFriday evening. The program was\n\"American Music\" and was ar\nranged by Mrs. James Homan. Ho\ntesses for the occasion were Mrs.\nJohn Jewell, Mrs. Jake Butler and\nMrs. Carlton Fooks.\nMrs. Viola Thistlewood returned\nto her home on Sunday after hav\ning spent the past month with Mr.\nand Mrs. John D. Kennedy and\ndaughters, Elaine and Kathleen, on\nOld Porter Road, Bear, Delaware.\nThe Kennedys accompanied Mrs.\nThistlewood home and they with\nMr. and Mrs. Emory Webb and\ndaughter Eileen were dinner guests\nof Mr. and Mrs. L. Paul Greenlee\nand sons, Larry and Tom on Shaw\nnee Road, near Milford.\nMrs. Annie Sharp, of Harrington,\nspent Sunday with Mf. and Mrs.\nGeorge B. Thistlewood and family.\nSunday dinner guests at the home\nof Mr. and Mrs. Clinton Marvel on\nSunday, were Mr. and Mrs. Albert\nLegar of near Millington, Md..\nMr. and Mrs. Oley F. Sapp and\nMr. and Mrs. C. Walter Wharton\nspent Sunday afternoon in Salis\nbury, Md.\nMr. George Simpson, who is quite\nill, is not much improved at this\ntime. We trust his recovery will be\nquick one.\nGrants Low Prices Help You Buy\nfor Mother\nMORE\nVa\nFind peak assortments,\nfashion-favored styles and\nfabrics, low-low prices.\n7:\not\nr\n\ny\nm\ngigs\nii\n2\nM\nI\nii\nm\n\nX\nIS\n\n\\W\nt\nVa\n\u00cf:\nip:\n/i\nV\nI\ns*.\nI\nT\n\nA\n\n!p$\ng\nj\n\nii\n\nfi\nW\nJig\nV\n\nVI\n4\n\n\nV\n\nI\nii\n\\f y\nI\nW'\nV\n\nJ\n\nN*:\n\nsr\n\n\n\n\nI I\nI\nm\n\u00ee\nI\nP\n\n\u00fc;\nM\njx\n\n\nXvvX\n\n\u00ff\nj.\n\n\n\n;r*\ng:\nuV\n4\n7*i\nVi\n\n\u00ee\nfi\nI\nill\n\nM:\nA\nv Duster N Scuffs\nt\ncare-free cotton plisse\nnever needs ironing\nI\nJVhat she wants lovely ho-iron slips\nW hat's her favorite ...new blends or nylon?\n\n\n\n\n2 98\nFLOWER-FRESH\nWOMEN'S SLIPS\n\n\u00dc\n1\ng\nSparkling with roses from\ntop to toe. Lustrous satin\npiping, fluffy pom-pom\nties. Light pink or blue.\nSizes 12 to 20; 40 to 44.\nOthers styles\nI\no?ily\nA bouquet of sweet slips!\nSome are runproof nylon,\nsome Dacron\u00ae, nylon, cotton\nblends. All treated to the\ntrims she likes best. Worth\nmore. Pastels, white. 32-44.\n2\n\u2022X\n98\n\n3.98\nii\n\n\nV\n5\nI\n\nm\n\u25a0m:\n\n'Y'S\nM-,\n\n\u25a0pg-'-fC\n\nn\n\ni-M:\nX,\ng\n\u25a0M:\nK\n\u00ff%m'\nI\nm\nA\n-4\n\nK';\ni 7\nI\n'M\nI\n186-COUNT PASTEL\nPERCALE SHEETS\nV.\nH\n2.49\ns\nHAPPY YOUNG\nPARAKEETS\nIMPORTED CHINA\nCUPS 7 N SAUCERS\n72x108\n*U17\n1.00\n3\ns\nSame quality in other fa\nmous makes up to 1.70\nmore.\n81x108 Sheets\n42x38'/2 Cases\nSETS\nLovable pets are a joy 